5000|$|A simpulum, or simpuvium, was a {{small vessel}} or ladle with a long handle from the Roman era, used at sacrifices to make libations, and <b>to</b> <b>taste</b> the <b>wines</b> and other liquors which were poured {{on the head of}} the {{sacrificial}} victims. The simpulum was the sign of Roman priesthood, and one of the insignia of the College of Pontiffs.|$|R
